289008;instagram;2018-10-16 19:34:11;FALSE;it's been 10 years as of yesterday.
the number of heartaches she encountered as a result.
always stumbling but never asked why.

column2: it was someone else. it's anyone but her. the questions swirling around and he wouldn't leave her alone no matter how many times she tried to get away.

column1: year 2: a serious relationship that turned abusive. she thought she deserved it because she was born into sin. things were spun around; that relationship made her believe what happened to her wasn't real until she too dove into the darkness.
year 3: she graduated and moved out only to move back home where her pain haunted her; her failures
year 4: the drugs and alcohol continued to take her for a spin. she met some people and felt free no matter how briefly it felt in the grand scheme of things. she felt true happiness.
year 5: relationship issues hit her yet again. back to the abuse
column2: one she couldn't say no to because she felt undeserving until finally she went away to regroup only to tumble down again.

column1: my latest article in today's dailyworld newspaper talks about the sensitive issue of those cases wherein some men get wrongly framed up under the charges of rape and then
column2: they undergo horrifying nightmares of life in the face of biased societal mindsets and prejudiced media trials and public opinions.

column1: it needs to be understood that not all men are historically and permanently wrong. similarly
column2: not all women are historically and permanently right. every case of alleged rape must be seriously and scientifically investigated before reaching the conclusion. media trials and public opinions based on unverifiable facts must be shunned. a real victim of rape deserves full justice under the law and the real perpetrators must be punished. however
column4: the cases where some innocent men are dubiously and wrongly framed up under rape charges must also be provided full justice and some women who misuse the provisions of rape law for settling personal revengeful scores or extorting monetary gains or attaining cheap publicity must be meted out the deserving punishment as they themselves do a great disservice to the cause of women justice involving real rape victims.

column1: and so much more we could never convey in words. .

our collective future is uncertain but we must proceed with ironclad will to manifest the highest vision of our own life and the lives of all those we are responsible for. .

column1: because we finally learned that no really means no. .
because we hurt enough people for this lifetime. .
because we're done acting like we have it all together when we really need help. .

because we are tired of lying to ourselves and the world about who we really are. .

because healthy intimate relationships with other human beings is the best ever. .
because we have committed to our personal healing and evolving into our highest self. .
because we are needed as a source of strength
because women and children have suffered by our hate and our hands for long enough. .

column1: 289190;instagram;2018-10-16 17:57:39;FALSE;"i guess it would be a disgrace to hold my silence whilst the issue is doing rounds.

column2: and when i say people i mean humans of every gender to please take the issue pretty seriously and not draw any humour out of it. it took women breathing in the patriarchal setups more than a thousand years to reach where we are. it is simply impossible to name how many people
column3: especially how many women have sacrificed all they had to bring women the rights they have today. cracking one joke about #metoo
column4: making memes on those who are being vocal about their assaults will take us light-years back.

column1: i urge people and when i say people i mean humans of every age to please not draw any advantage out if this wave
column2: to please clear the field and give the victims a chance to raise their voice. please do not use this to falsely accuse anyone
column3: be it that ex of yours or that colleague at work you never liked for reasons beyond harrassing behaviour
column4: cause if you do that there'll be a thousand women who will go unheard in the ruckus.

column1: my mother admits quitting a job due to her senior's behavioural misconduct at work back in 1985. there can be no estimation of how many women quit their jobs due to the same issue. i urge you not to create mockery out of an issue as sensitive as this. read some literature
column2: delve deeper into the world history
column3: there are tonnes of women who have literally slashed their souls and squeezed out every drop of power within it to create a ladder for women to climb and reach where men have lived since time immemorial.

column1: 289348;instagram;2018-10-16 16:41:05;FALSE;"this weekend's on the other side of #metoo's photo shoot arrived with an invitation to directly express my sexual essence as beauty
column4: as a mature embodied woman.  i chose to go over the edge of some invisible retaining wall i had built to hold back and hold in.  what unfolded was unfiltered expression.

column1: today i'm feeling quiet tender power. openness. steady in my core and a new vulnerability.
there were aspects of myself that locked down
column2: split apart and were held back and unexpressed due to sexual trauma.  as i heal together
column3: i choose.  i choose to open those doors. express more of my fullness and wholeness.  and there are guardians at those gates. guardians that need my accompaniment

column1: for many years i've held an subconscious belief that if i directly expressed my sexual essence it would somehow validate that is was my fault.  that there was something inherently bad and wrong with me.  that i deserved.  walking past that belief on sunday has brought more to the surface to be loved into wholeness.  last night i awoke at 3 a.m.  went outside and looked at the big dipper hanging in the night sky.  sat on the edge of my bed and ran my hands over my thighs (i think that's a part of the body that's known to house shame)
column3: it's already ok."" #metoo is a movement. moving from the shadows into the light of a new day.  we can do this. we heal together or not at all.

column1: 289470;instagram;2018-10-16 15:30:25;FALSE;"ok so as yesterday was the 1st year anniversary of the #metoomovement i wanted to come out about something. i was sexually assaulted. around a year and a half to two years ago so before #metoo was a thing. i was so scared. my assaulter attended school with me and still does because even though my mum knew and got the police involved

column4: on the way to and from school

column1: 289554;instagram;2018-10-16 15:04:36;FALSE;"the #metoo movement is one year old. it is a movement against sexual harassment and assault. the #metoo hashtag is used on social media to demonstrate the widespread prevalence of sexual assault and harassment women endure too frequently.
i strongly feel it is so much more than that. it is a strong resilience process that started. women are showing to the world their resilience capacities.
1. sorority: this digital hashtag enables women to connect (digitally) with each other in support for each other. it is the pillar number one of resilience: seek and get support.
2. deal with shame: by talking publicly under the #metoo flag
column2: every single individual who faced and overcame the shame from sexual assault is dealing with it. it is pillar number two of resilience.

column1: 3. tell your story: most hashtag has been accompanied by a description of facts or a story. being able to articulate what happened is the pillar number 3 of resilience. words heal.
is the world ready to listen to these stories and trigger a true societal change?
i am curious....hopefully curious. one year is too young to draw a conclusion.

column1: i'm not shy when it comes to sharing my story. and i share because i know the power my story has to empower others who have walked in my shoes. there are far too many who understand the pain... the confusion... the fear... the secrecy.
but i am not a victim. i am a survivor. and if you also resonate with ""me too"" as it pertains to the current trend on social media
column2: then you too are also a survivor. don't you forget it.

column1: while being raped and getting pregnant from my assailant certainly wasn't ideal - at 19 or any age - i am grateful.
the experience of sexual assault taught me a lot. not only about humanity
it taught me about my own inner strength...
it taught me about true resilience...
it taught me about my ability to forgive and use my pain for good... to help others heal and know it's okay not to be okay.
rape is not a term to be used lightly. it's not a term to be used in the context i hear so often in joking manners or to describe being taken advantage of
rape gets to be an open conversation we continue to have until it stops.
because there are people - men and women - all over the world facing this terrible act every day.
we have a responsibility to create awareness and be a catalyst for change. we get to create safety for the survivors to speak out and be heard without judgement or pity.

column3: are not broken. we are brave. we are brilliant. we are you and me.â¤ï¸

column1: 289734;instagram;2018-10-16 13:41:31;FALSE;"national | #metoo â€“ mj akbar hires 97 lawyers against priya ramani
details: following the charges of sexual misconduct levied by journalist priya ramani
column2: minister of state for external affairs mj akbar on monday filed a criminal defamation complaint against her. surprisingly
column3: 97 lawyers of a law firm have been roped in to defend akbar in this case.

column1: the law firm hired to defend akbar
column3: called the mention of the 97 advocates in the vakalatnama as the ""standard practice"" and said only six are meant to appear in the court for him. â€œour firm has 100 lawyers. we usually have all the names printed in one vakalatnama with only the ones who will appear in the case signing it. our criminal team has six members and only those six will appear in this case. only they have signed the vakalatnama
column4: â€ a spokesperson of the firm was quoted as saying.

column2: the news about 97 lawyers working to defend akbar drew sharp reactions on social media. pointing that this showed the consequences ""lone voices"" have to face for speaking out
column3: several journalists and other twitter users sided with ramani.

pelecehan seksual di awal karirnya saqib saleem adalah yang terbaru untuk berbagi memori traumatiknya dimana dirinya menghadapi serangan seksual pada usia 21 tahun di ruang profesional . ketika berbicara dengan media , saqib berkata , â€œ ya , saya tidak ingin mengambil nama , tetapi ketika saya mulai sebagai aktor , saya baru berusia 21 tahun saat itu dan ada seorang pria yang mencoba tindakannya yang menjijikkan , saqib memukulnya , bukan karena seksualitasnya tetapi karena tindakannya . â€œ saya punya teman gay dan mereka adalah teman-teman paling indah yang pernah saya miliki . saya tidak menyalahkan seksualitas seseorang dalam masalah ini , tapi itu adalah mentalitas orang itu . ketika itu terjadi dengan saya , saya memukul orang itu dan saya mengatakan kepadanya untuk memikirkan bisnisnya sendiri , dan saya pergi . saya berusia 21 tahun , dan tentu saja , itu melelahkan saya , tetapi saya pindah . saya yakin setiap orang berbeda dan insiden sepei ini pasti mempengaruhi orang berbeda secara berbeda â€ , jelas saqib kepada media . saqib juga mengatakan bahwa ia sangat merasakan untuk para korban sepei ia telah tumbuh di antara perempuan dan memiliki rasa hormat yang mendalam kepada mereka . â€œ saya juga menghadapinya . saya dapat berempati dengan setiap gadis yang telah dilecehkan . itu membuat saya jijik , jadi saya tahu apa yang dialami wanita . setiap pelaku seksual di luar sana harus dihukum dengan cara yang paling berat â€ . namun , saudara laki-laki huma qureshi juga berpendapat bahwa gerakan yang sensitif dan kuat sepei tidak boleh column1: 289880;instagram;2018-10-16 12:11:15;FALSE;"â€œthe darkest period of my life was in the 9th grade. we learnt what sex was in school & it all just hit me. the flashbacks started & i realised that i had been sexually abused as a child. when i was 5
column2: my parents would drop me to a daycare. there was another girl who looked like meâ€“chubby & dark skinned. the nannyâ€™d nap in the afternoon & her son would take turns to molest us. he would rub his penis on our bodies.
my behaviour changedâ€“my grades started slipping
column3: i started eating less & withdrawing from people. i blamed myself. years of body image issues & battling insecurities led me to believe that god was punishing me. my mom noticed this sudden change & i finally told her in the 10th grade. she was shatteredâ€“she started crying. she blamed herself too & apologised for not protecting me.

column1: i told her it wasnâ€™t her fault & we tried to move on. but
column2: when i moved to kolkata to study political scienceâ€“it brought up the past again. i was out with my friends when i saw a man brutally hitting the woman with him. i was horrified. we tried to get help from a traffic policeman & he ignored us. finally
column3: we spoke to 2 policemen & waited there until they came with us. when they reached & talked to the woman
column4: she started crying & defended the man. there was nothing anyone could do if the woman wasnâ€™t ready to file an fir.

column1: i realised that was the problem. as a woman
column2: you think you deserve to be mistreated & you accept that as your reality. i tried to move on & forget. but
column3: it all changed when i met a friend in college & opened up to him. he made me realise that my story was worth sharing & i wasnâ€™t at fault. the only way to get past it was to accept. i had had enough of this anonymity-why should it be my shame?i posted my story on instagram during the me too movement & so many people in my college followed. it made me realise how common it is.

column1: most people never want to face their abuser again. but i want to confront mine to let him know that what he did was reckless & affected my entire life. itâ€™s 15 years later & iâ€™m still trying to heal...were 5 minutes of his sick pleasure
column2: worth an entire life of pleasure
column3: worth an entire life of pain?""

column1: a fear of not being believed was just one of many reasons why i found it hard to report what happened to me when i was 15 to the police

earlier this year i finally made the call and i can't begin to explain just how life-changing it was to have the police officers say they believe me. i met six officers/detectives in total and not once did they make me feel as though they doubted my side of the story
and even though there wasn't enough evidence to take things to court
column2: feeling as though the police were on my side is helping with the whole 'healing' process. i no longer feel like what happened to me was my fault and i don't feel responsible for anything else he went on to do afterwards. i do regret not saying something sooner
column3: but i'm proud of myself for finally coming forward and telling the police what happened

column2: behind closed doors i suspect the police will have had a discussion about whether i had any reason to lie. that's an important part of the job

column1: for all those people offended with and questioning my recent outing for #navratri event i have some words of common sense to share..why do u expect me or anyone who has spoken out about injustice to just stay at home and sulk.ive never done that and never will.i have been attending events for the last 10 years regularly and looking great and happy is my birthright as a human being.im a 21st century girl and i don't conform to how your primitive mindset would  expect me to behave.
dont forget that i have an identity beyond the cause i'm currently championing ; i am the miss india universe
column2: lead actress of several mainstream films and public figure who holds her own space in this world.

column1: this raises an important topic of why girls and women when they have the courage to speak out about harassment
column2: abuse or assault are then further stigmatized by society by imposing on them rules and codes of conduct post complaint.

column1: for the last 10 years i have seen the four harassers of horn ok please incident go out and about their life
column4: win awards and laugh and smile and get accolades etc..why not raise a question then?? now is my time!! i will continue to raise awareness with my activism
column6: i will go out and have a great time with friends and family
column8: i will bring hope to many that have lost hope in this darkness
column9: i will show a way to healing and wholeness to those that are broken.i will shine my light bright for all to see as i was not created to lurk in the shadows.and all this i will do while looking stunning
column10: fantabulous and awesome!! im a child of god and i do things differently from most others.im genx.

column1: so to all naysayers: look how i will  hold my peace
column2: prosper and  grow in the midst of a storm.my enemies shall be my footstools and i shall rise high upon wings like eagles..if u dont like it too bad eat your hearts out!!- quoted #tanushreedutta

column1: for all those people offended with and questioning my recent outing for  event i have some words of common sense to share..why do u expect me or anyone who has spoken out about injustice to just stay at home and sulk.ive never done that and never will.i have been attending events for the last 10 years regularly and looking great and happy is my bihright as a human being.im a 21st century girl and i do not conform to how your primitive mindset would  expect me to behave.
do not forget that i have an identity beyond the cause i am currently championing ; i am the miss india universe
column2: lead actress of several mainstream films and public figure who holds her own space in this world.

in this poignant memoir of personal transformation
column2: jill soloway takes us on a patriarchy-toppling emotional and professional journey. when jill's parent came out as transgender
column3: jill pushed through the male-dominated landscape of hollywood to create the groundbreaking and award-winning amazon tv series transparent. exploring identity
column6: and the blurring of boundaries through the dynamics of a complicated and profoundly resonant american family
column7: transparent gave birth to a new cultural consciousness. while working on the show and exploding mainstream ideas about gender
column8: jill began to erase the lines on their own map
column9: finding their voice as a director

column3: and toppling the patriarchy moves with urgent rhythms
column5: and razor-edged humor to chart jill's evolution from straight
column6: married mother of two to identifying as queer and nonbinary. this intense and revelatory metamorphosis challenges the status quo and reflects the shifting power dynamics that continue to shape our collective worldview. with unbridled insight that offers a rare front seat to the inner workings of the #metoo movement and its aftermath
column7: jill captures the zeitgeist of a generation with thoughtful and revolutionary ideas about gender

column1: 289988;instagram;2018-10-16 10:46:12;FALSE;"to all the people slamming this movement.
to all the men getting offended without even knowing the real objective behind.
to all the women who used their rights immorally for their revenge.

this isn't just a hash tag or a trend. it was started by @taranajaneen  12 years ago. it was intended to let the victims or we can say survivors to come upfront and talk about it. 'me too' is about letting and using the power of empathy to stomp out shame.
the work is more than just amplification of survivors and quantifying their numbers. the real work was about survivors talking to each other
it's a rainbow of 'women supporting women'. it's the movement of healing the unhealed. it's the empowerment through empathy.
it's a blessing to be privileged but to use it for the service of others is the way out of the box.
